{
  "doc_id": "26100",
  "text": "Bardet-Biedl syndrome affects the function of nonmotile cilia and leads to obesity, RP, the formation of extra digits, hypogonadism, and kidney problems [CITATION_1] . The first successful gene-based treatment of BardetBiedl syndrome-associated retinal degeneration was demonstrated in a Bbs4-null mouse model, where an AAV-based vector expressing BBS4 prevented photoreceptor death, improved retinal function, and visually evoked behavior responses, providing hope for a promising future therapy in humans [CITATION_2] .",
